-- Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: CFC Stanbic, FTN Cocoa, Naiade Resorts
-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k   a n d   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a
-- 2010-12-22T16:53:39Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-22/sub-saharan-africa-equities-report-cfc-stanbic-ftn-cocoa-naiade-resorts.html
Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  snapped two
days of losses, rising 1 percent to 1,913.79 by the 1:30 p.m.
close in Port Louis.  Kenya’s  All-Share Index  increased 0.1 percent to 77.58 by
the close at 3 p.m. in Nairobi, the first advance in three days.
The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index  added the most in a
week, gaining 0.7 percent to 24,591.58 by the 2:30 p.m. close in
Lagos, according to an e-mailed statement from the bourse.
Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  rose for a fifth day,
adding 0.4 percent to 861.91 by the 5 p.m. close in Windhoek
while the  Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share Index  retreated 0.1
percent to 7,180.9 by the 1 p.m. close in Accra, a third day of
decreases.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  CFC Stanbic Bank Ltd.  (CFCB KN), Standard Bank Group Ltd.’s
Kenyan unit, snapped two days of declines, rising 1 shilling, or
1.4 percent, to 71.5 shillings. Kenya’s financial services
industry grew 20 percent in the third quarter, compared with
expansion of 7.1 percent a year earlier, the Nairobi-based
statistics office said in a report yesterday. East Africa’s
biggest economy rose an annual 6.1 percent in the third quarter,
the fastest pace in three years.  Housing Finance Ltd.  (HFCL KN), Kenya’s only publicly
traded mortgage company, surged 25 cents, or 1 percent, to 25
shillings.  FTN Cocoa Processors Plc  (FTNCOCOA NL), a Nigerian producer
of commodities from the chocolate ingredient, fell the most in
two weeks, dropping 3 kobo, or 4.6 percent, to 62 kobo. Profit
declined 94 percent to 12.4 million naira ($80,400) from 205.7
million naira a year earlier, according to a statement on the
website of the Lagos-based Nigerian Stock Exchange dated
yesterday. The bourse described the period as the third quarter.  Naiade Resorts Ltd. (NRL MP), a Mauritian hotel operator,
climbed the most in 11 weeks, increasing 1.4 rupees, or 6.5
percent, to 22.9 rupees, after New Mauritius Hotels Ltd., the
nation’s biggest leisure group by market value, said it expects
growth to improve, boosting industry prospects.  New Mauritius Hotels’ earnings for the first quarter
through December are expected to be around 10 percent more than
last year’s, it said in a statement on the Stock Exchange of
Mauritius’s website yesterday. “Investors deduced that it would
be same for other hotel counters,” Vikash Tulsidas, manager at
Port Louis-based AXYS Stockbroking Ltd., said in a phone
interview today from the city.  To contact the reporters on this story:
